Title: Boom Town: The Fantastical Saga of Oklahoma City, Its Chaotic Founding, Its Apocalyptic Weather, Its Purloined Basketball Team, and the Dream of Becoming a World-class Metropolis
Author: Sam Anderson
My Review: Picked this up because of the passing mention of basketball on the cover. Put it down and didn’t want it to end. A fascinating biography of a city that I had never been curious about. So many memorable stories of OKC’s origins, aspirations and strife. Plus, the portion of the book about the basketball team (maybe 20%) is excellent. The Thunder are somehow a very apt metaphor for the city. Oftentimes the best sports writing comes from an outsider’s perspective.

Title: Behind the Beautiful Forevers: Life, Death, and Hope in a Mumbai Undercity
Author: Katherine Boo
My Review:
I admit I prejudged this book by its author: I wondered if a white person could do justice to the story of a Mumbai slum. After finishing, I’m thankful for the incredible efforts Katherine Boo took to explain this small part of the world. She covers thoroughly the persistent strife that comes with living in such poverty while narrating dramatic tales of how the slum came to be, why the slum dwellers were always at odds and what they did to survive. It’s a story informed by anthropology and virtually no topic is uncovered: religion, politics, economics, the criminal justice system and more.

My earlier concerns were assuaged after reading her author’s note detailing her reporting process at the end of the book. Plus, as an Indian, I appreciated the way she wove in particular turns of phrase and certain non-verbal cues that showed to me she understood the communication between the people she covered, despite not knowing the languages herself.

This particular slum comes right up to the perimeter of the airport in Bombay and I was always curious about it on childhood visits. I’m glad I finally got to learn more about it.
